    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:10c9bca5-7609-434c-8f7e-dd29fafd772d",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 14-year-old boy from the Czech Republic who is brought to clinic because teachers and parents have noticed persistent inattention, hyperactivity, and impulsive behavior across both school and home settings over several years, consistent with disturbance of activity and attention [SNOMED:F90.0]. He often starts tasks but loses focus quickly, misses details, forgets instructions, and needs repeated redirection. During the interview he appears physically well and casually dressed, but he is restless, frequently shifting in his seat, fidgeting with his sleeves, glancing around the room, and answering before questions are fully finished.\n\nAt school, {patientName} enjoys computer games and football with friends, but he struggles to complete assignments on time because he becomes sidetracked by noises, conversations, or his own thoughts. Teachers report that he has difficulty remaining seated, talks out of turn, and makes careless mistakes despite understanding the material. He also shows productive executive difficulties: he loses worksheets, forgets homework, has trouble organizing multi-step tasks, and underestimates how long schoolwork will take.\n\nAt home, family members describe emotional lability and impulsivity, with blurting out comments, interrupting others, becoming frustrated quickly, and having trouble waiting his turn during conversations or games. He leaves chores unfinished unless closely supervised and often moves from one activity to another without completing the first. Despite these challenges, he has a supportive family and a small group of friends, and he enjoys activities that provide immediate feedback and movement. He denies current physical illness, and there are no concerning somatic symptoms beyond the behavioral and attention-related difficulties documented for this disorder."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:599efbfd-f3da-4d7d-98bf-715a3d95fedd",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has had concentration and behavior difficulties since early primary school, not just the current academic year, with repeated teacher reports of inattention, excessive talking, restlessness, incomplete work, and needing frequent redirection. His parents describe impulsive emotional reactions at home, including interrupting, acting before thinking, difficulty waiting his turn, and becoming overwhelmed during homework that requires sustained mental effort. He also has a history of mild chronic sleep-onset difficulty and specific learning difficulties in written school tasks, both of which can worsen attentional control and functional impairment.\n\nPregnancy and birth history are notable for maternal smoking during pregnancy and late-preterm birth at 36 weeks, both recognized risk factors associated with later attention and activity regulation problems. There is no history of major medical illness or prior hospitalization, and he has not undergone prior surgery. He lives with his parents, attends school regularly, and participates in recreational sports.\n\nFamily history is relevant: his father had childhood attention-deficit/hyperactivity disorder symptoms that persisted into adolescence, and his maternal uncle has a diagnosis of hyperkinetic disorder/ADHD. His mother has generalized anxiety symptoms, providing related psychiatric family history. Current background medication is cetirizine for seasonal allergic rhinitis. He also intermittently uses inhaled salbutamol for mild asthma symptoms during exercise; while not a cause of ADHD, stimulant-like side effects such as jitteriness or restlessness can sometimes accentuate hyperactivity-like behavior and are important to document when assessing symptoms."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
